According to the Jinja2 documentation, `{% set %}` operations are evaluated at **parse time**, not at runtime. This means that the expression inside the `{% set %}` block is evaluated when the template is parsed, before the template is rendered.

In your example, the `{% set thing = function_with_side_effects() %}` line will be evaluated when the template is parsed, regardless of the value of `var`. This means that `function_with_side_effects()` will be called, even if the `if` condition is not met.

So, unfortunately, it is not safe to assume that the `{% set %}` operation will not be evaluated if the surrounding block is not included due to conditional operations.

To avoid calling `function_with_side_effects()` when `var != 1`, you can use a different approach, such as:

```jinja2
{% if var == 1 %}
   {% set thing = function_with_side_effects() %}
   {{ thing }}
{% endif %}
```

Or, if you want to avoid calling the function altogether, you can use a lazy evaluation approach, such as:

```jinja2
{% if var == 1 %}
   {% set thing = (function_with_side_effects)() %}
   {{ thing }}
{% endif %}
```

In this case, the `function_with_side_effects` function will only be called when the `if` condition is true, and the result will be assigned to the `thing` variable.

Keep in mind that this behavior is specific to Jinja2's `{% set %}` operation, and might not apply to other templating engines or programming languages.

